JEANNE SAUVAGE: You
know, I hope to.

00:40:27.890 --> 00:40:29.720
That is something
that's in the works.

00:40:29.720 --> 00:40:31.810
So yeah, I hope to do that.

00:40:31.810 --> 00:40:34.335
And I have all of these
things on my site as well.

00:40:34.335 --> 00:40:35.710
So I've got the
pizza on my site,

00:40:35.710 --> 00:40:38.150
I've got puff pastry
on my site, I've

00:40:38.150 --> 00:40:41.620
got pasta dough on my site.

00:40:41.620 --> 00:40:45.660
And I guess the
end, there you go.

00:40:45.660 --> 00:40:48.310
But yeah, I have a ton
of stuff on my site

00:40:48.310 --> 00:40:50.450
that are-- it's all free.

00:40:50.450 --> 00:40:53.220
And I also answer
questions so people often

00:40:53.220 --> 00:40:57.450
will write me and say, this
is my family's special recipe

00:40:57.450 --> 00:41:01.360
for German coffee cake and would
you be willing to adapt it?

00:41:01.360 --> 00:41:03.520
And if I have the
time and I want to I

00:41:03.520 --> 00:41:06.030
will do that for folks.

00:41:06.030 --> 00:41:08.341
I mean if I become
super duper popular

00:41:08.341 --> 00:41:09.840
I don't know how
much I can do that.

00:41:09.840 --> 00:41:13.810
But that's part of what
I-- Earlier this year I

00:41:13.810 --> 00:41:17.380
wanted to define for myself what
my goal was with all of this.

00:41:17.380 --> 00:41:20.600
I mean my first goal,
of course, was for me.

00:41:20.600 --> 00:41:23.090
I wanted to be able
to eat these things.

00:41:23.090 --> 00:41:25.690
But my second goal
is to serve people,

00:41:25.690 --> 00:41:28.780
to help folks be
able to eat again.

00:41:28.780 --> 00:41:31.650
And to be able to bake again
and be able to enjoy this again.

00:41:31.650 --> 00:41:35.430
And so I wanna
really continue that,

00:41:35.430 --> 00:41:37.680
and that's why I try to
be as successful as I

00:41:37.680 --> 00:41:39.630
can on social media
and on my site.

00:41:39.630 --> 00:41:42.720
Because I really want
to help out folks.

00:41:42.720 --> 00:41:44.570
AUDIENCE: More of a
curiosity, I noticed

00:41:44.570 --> 00:41:47.680
that in your recipe for the
flour, one of the ingredients

00:41:47.680 --> 00:41:50.619
is glutenous rice flour, which
I assume does not have gluten.

00:41:50.619 --> 00:41:51.410
JEANNE SAUVAGE: No.

00:41:51.410 --> 00:41:54.980
AUDIENCE: But is it just a lot
of starch, or what makes it

00:41:54.980 --> 00:41:55.690
glutenous?

00:41:55.690 --> 00:41:57.540
JEANNE SAUVAGE: Yeah
it has a lot of starch.

00:41:57.540 --> 00:42:01.080
It's also known as sticky rice
flour and the glutenous part,

00:42:01.080 --> 00:42:03.750
as you picked up, it
just means it's sticky.

00:42:03.750 --> 00:42:06.760
It's called sweet rice
flour most of the time.

00:42:06.760 --> 00:42:08.850
You can buy it in
the supermarket

00:42:08.850 --> 00:42:12.310
often in the ethics section
in a little white box that's

00:42:12.310 --> 00:42:14.750
labeled mochiko.

00:42:14.750 --> 00:42:17.380
And it's used a lot
in Asian baking.

00:42:17.380 --> 00:42:18.420
But it is confusing.

00:42:18.420 --> 00:42:21.157
I get tons of questions
about, you're gluten free

00:42:21.157 --> 00:42:22.865
and you use glutenous
rice flour and so I

00:42:22.865 --> 00:42:25.950
have to explain that the rice is
not a gluten containing grain.

00:42:25.950 --> 00:42:29.050
So it's just a weird
thing, I don't know why.

00:42:29.050 --> 00:42:33.270
But it actually is a really
good part of the mix.

00:42:33.270 --> 00:42:36.870
In addition to the xanthan gun,
it helps bring things together,

00:42:36.870 --> 00:42:39.200
which I think is nice.

00:42:39.200 --> 00:42:42.070
Another thing, just
talking about my mix,

00:42:42.070 --> 00:42:44.860
I recommend to folks so
you see this in my book

00:42:44.860 --> 00:42:47.190
and I have it on my
site but I recommend

00:42:47.190 --> 00:42:50.350
that if you are
sensitive to graininess--

00:42:50.350 --> 00:42:52.360
this is one of the
issues that often happens

00:42:52.360 --> 00:42:54.350
with gluten free
flour, always look

00:42:54.350 --> 00:42:57.930
for the finely ground flours.

00:42:57.930 --> 00:43:01.350
So like there's extra
fine grind brown rice

00:43:01.350 --> 00:43:02.810
flour that you can find.

00:43:02.810 --> 00:43:06.320
Now if you can't find it and
you're just using brown rice

00:43:06.320 --> 00:43:09.400
flour-- like I use the
flours from Bob's Red Mill,

00:43:09.400 --> 00:43:12.930
I use flours from
Authentic Foods.

00:43:12.930 --> 00:43:16.580
Authentic Foods has the extra
fine grind but Bob's doesn't.

00:43:16.580 --> 00:43:18.617
And if it bothers you
enough you can just

00:43:18.617 --> 00:43:20.575
stick it in your blender
or your food processor

00:43:20.575 --> 00:43:23.800
and grind it up a little more
and make it a little more fine.

00:43:23.800 --> 00:43:26.970
So that works too.

00:43:26.970 --> 00:43:31.430
The one I would not recommend
in terms of the mix,

00:43:31.430 --> 00:43:35.740
you asked about mix, the Bob's
Red Mill Mix, is not so good.

00:43:35.740 --> 00:43:37.430
Do you guys have
Bob's Red Mill here?

00:43:37.430 --> 00:43:38.790
Yeah OK.

00:43:38.790 --> 00:43:40.390
It has a lot of
bean flour in it.

00:43:40.390 --> 00:43:43.250
And it's just very
strong tasting.

00:43:43.250 --> 00:43:46.180
And I don't know why
they keep having it.

00:43:46.180 --> 00:43:49.740
But when you make things--
so part of when I bake,

00:43:49.740 --> 00:43:50.584
like I bake cookies.

00:43:50.584 --> 00:43:52.000
I eat some of
cookie dough, that's

00:43:52.000 --> 00:43:53.440
just kind of part of what I do.

00:43:53.440 --> 00:43:55.970
You cannot do that when
there's a bean flour involved

00:43:55.970 --> 00:44:00.450
because it's so strong and
it's so yucky, basically.

00:44:00.450 --> 00:44:02.930
That's why I recommend stay
away from the bean flours.

00:44:02.930 --> 00:44:05.970
Also the bean flours
are very high in protein

00:44:05.970 --> 00:44:07.970
and they go rancid very quickly.

00:44:07.970 --> 00:44:10.950
So you need to store those
in the freezer usually.

00:44:10.950 --> 00:44:13.740
And I have that in my book
and on my site but something

00:44:13.740 --> 00:44:15.770
to keep in mind.

00:44:15.770 --> 00:44:18.770
Did that answer your question
about the glutenous rice?

00:44:18.770 --> 00:44:19.952
So more questions?

00:44:19.952 --> 00:44:21.410
AUDIENCE: So you
mentioned you have

00:44:21.410 --> 00:44:24.520
people ask you to
adapt lots of recipes.

00:44:24.520 --> 00:44:27.680
When you're doing
that adaptation,

00:44:27.680 --> 00:44:30.470
what would you say is the most
common change you're making?

00:44:30.470 --> 00:44:33.480
JEANNE SAUVAGE: Well
the flour, of course.

00:44:33.480 --> 00:44:36.690
The other, probably the two
most common changes I make

00:44:36.690 --> 00:44:38.710
is in terms of the leaveners.

00:44:38.710 --> 00:44:41.810
So often things don't
have enough leavening.

00:44:41.810 --> 00:44:44.570
And when I say leavener, I mean
the thing that makes it rise,

00:44:44.570 --> 00:44:47.540
so baking powder,
baking soda, yeast.

00:44:47.540 --> 00:44:51.990
So most gluten free recipes I
found need more of those things

00:44:51.990 --> 00:44:53.120
often.

00:44:53.120 --> 00:44:56.060
Now using classic
baking techniques

00:44:56.060 --> 00:44:57.920
actually sometimes
makes it so you

00:44:57.920 --> 00:45:00.550
don't have to because
you're creating the air

00:45:00.550 --> 00:45:02.840
pockets that the
leaveners can work on.

00:45:02.840 --> 00:45:08.100
For example, you beat the
fat and the sugar together.

00:45:08.100 --> 00:45:10.890
So it's the leaveners
that I often do.

00:45:10.890 --> 00:45:12.090
Sometimes eggs.

00:45:12.090 --> 00:45:14.370
I find that there's
not enough eggs

00:45:14.370 --> 00:45:17.620
in baking to create
the moisture and also

00:45:17.620 --> 00:45:20.040
to create some of the structure.

00:45:20.040 --> 00:45:24.440
And then with yeast, you
need to have much more yeast

00:45:24.440 --> 00:45:25.650
than you would normally have.

00:45:25.650 --> 00:45:32.120
Those are probably the most
common changes that I make.

00:45:32.120 --> 00:45:34.330
And the other thing is
gluten free things seem

00:45:34.330 --> 00:45:37.630
to take a little bit
longer to cook, to bake.

00:45:37.630 --> 00:45:40.900
So I often either increase
the temperature or at least

00:45:40.900 --> 00:45:42.410
I increase the time.

00:45:42.410 --> 00:45:45.290
And I think part of that
is-- Do you guys know

00:45:45.290 --> 00:45:46.860
the concept of hydration?

00:45:46.860 --> 00:45:51.620
So in baking parlance
the hydration of a dough

00:45:51.620 --> 00:45:55.850
is the percentage of the
water or liquid in a dough.

00:45:55.850 --> 00:45:58.500
And I have found that
gluten free things

00:45:58.500 --> 00:46:01.260
do well with more liquid
in it, more water,

00:46:01.260 --> 00:46:04.650
because they dry out
much more quickly.

00:46:04.650 --> 00:46:08.360
And I think that then leads
to a longer baking time

00:46:08.360 --> 00:46:11.870
because you need to
bake some of that out.

00:46:11.870 --> 00:46:13.080
Is that helpful?

00:46:13.080 --> 00:46:16.040
There's one thing
that's hard, is

00:46:16.040 --> 00:46:18.042
I try to tell
people, for example

00:46:18.042 --> 00:46:19.500
if you have a cookie
recipe and you

00:46:19.500 --> 00:46:22.260
want to adapt it, I just
tell people use my mix.

00:46:22.260 --> 00:46:25.490
Use the cup for cup for the
wheat flour in your recipe,

00:46:25.490 --> 00:46:26.890
see what happens.

00:46:26.890 --> 00:46:30.250
And for something like a
cookie that usually suffices.

00:46:30.250 --> 00:46:32.140
Then you get a little
more complicated,

00:46:32.140 --> 00:46:34.792
you get into muffins and scones.

00:46:34.792 --> 00:46:36.750
Sometimes you need tweaks,
sometimes you don't.

00:46:36.750 --> 00:46:39.140
Get into cakes, that's
more complicated.

00:46:39.140 --> 00:46:42.650
But I always tell people to
try and see what happens.

00:46:42.650 --> 00:46:45.800
And then once they
see what happens,

00:46:45.800 --> 00:46:47.680
if it's not to their
liking they can kind of

00:46:47.680 --> 00:46:50.380
reverse engineer what happened.

00:46:50.380 --> 00:46:51.390
So was it too dry?

00:46:51.390 --> 00:46:54.980
OK it's too dry, add more
eggs or add more liquid.

00:46:54.980 --> 00:46:55.890
Didn't rise.

00:46:55.890 --> 00:46:59.431
OK did you beat the eggs,
the fat, and the sugar?

00:46:59.431 --> 00:46:59.930
Yes.

00:46:59.930 --> 00:47:01.075
OK you need more leavener.

00:47:05.070 --> 00:47:08.790
Did it come out kind of
wet after you've baked it?

00:47:08.790 --> 00:47:09.290
Yes.

00:47:09.290 --> 00:47:11.100
OK you need to raise
baking temperature.

00:47:11.100 --> 00:47:12.740
You need to put it in longer.

00:47:12.740 --> 00:47:16.100
So I think I ultimately would
like to get to the point

00:47:16.100 --> 00:47:20.440
where I can teach people
to do this themselves.

00:47:20.440 --> 00:47:24.210
But each recipe seems
to be its own bird.

00:47:24.210 --> 00:47:27.840
And so, so far I haven't
been able to say,

00:47:27.840 --> 00:47:32.190
for all muffins you need to
make this adaptation, that kind

00:47:32.190 --> 00:47:32.690
of thing.

00:47:32.690 --> 00:47:34.190
So that's what makes
it complicated.

00:47:34.190 --> 00:47:36.510
But I tell people to try
and see what happens.

00:47:36.510 --> 00:47:39.670
But one thing you can't
adapt cup for cup at all

00:47:39.670 --> 00:47:41.240
is a yeasted recipe.

00:47:41.240 --> 00:47:44.560
Yeasted recipes are
their whole other bird.

00:47:44.560 --> 00:47:47.720
You need more yeast,
you need more liquid,

00:47:47.720 --> 00:47:50.460
often you need more
eggs, you need more time.

00:47:50.460 --> 00:47:53.550
And so when people tried
to do, for example,

00:47:53.550 --> 00:47:57.610
they try to do their
moms bread with my flour

00:47:57.610 --> 00:47:59.180
mixture it doesn't work so well.

00:47:59.180 --> 00:48:01.100
Because there's so many
different variables

00:48:01.100 --> 00:48:02.580
that go into a yeasted thing.

00:48:02.580 --> 00:48:04.720
So that's a challenge.

00:48:04.720 --> 00:48:06.490
Although like I said
I do have a sourdough

00:48:06.490 --> 00:48:09.870
on my site, which is fun because
you develop your own sourdough

00:48:09.870 --> 00:48:10.930
starter.

00:48:10.930 --> 00:48:12.660
And then from there
you make the bread

00:48:12.660 --> 00:48:14.790
which is a fun-- if you
like that kind of thing--

00:48:14.790 --> 00:48:16.250
it's a fun process.

00:48:16.250 --> 00:48:19.340
And I harvest the wild yeast.

00:48:19.340 --> 00:48:21.870
I don't use commercial
yeast, I harvest wild yeast

00:48:21.870 --> 00:48:23.270
and I show you how to do that.

00:48:23.270 --> 00:48:25.340
So that's kind of fun.

00:48:25.340 --> 00:48:27.230
AUDIENCE: So a lot of
the gluten free baking

00:48:27.230 --> 00:48:30.950
I do is for somebody who
is also rice intolerant

00:48:30.950 --> 00:48:33.214
and I encounter that a lot
in the recipes in your--

00:48:33.214 --> 00:48:34.130
JEANNE SAUVAGE: Right.

00:48:34.130 --> 00:48:35.620
AUDIENCE: --mix.

00:48:35.620 --> 00:48:38.160
So any suggestions
for direction to go

00:48:38.160 --> 00:48:41.270
if rice flour is not
really an option?

00:48:41.270 --> 00:48:42.490
JEANNE SAUVAGE: Yes.

00:48:42.490 --> 00:48:44.660
In my book, if you've
got the book I've got,

00:48:44.660 --> 00:48:48.600
some substitutions--
like for, with for the--

00:48:48.600 --> 00:48:51.000
so I don't think I can
remember all of them.

00:48:51.000 --> 00:48:54.100
I have it on my site but I
think it's for the-- now this

00:48:54.100 --> 00:48:57.530
will alter my mix and
things will behave and taste

00:48:57.530 --> 00:48:58.350
a little different.

00:48:58.350 --> 00:49:00.920
But for the brown
rice flour it'll

00:49:00.920 --> 00:49:02.430
tell you substitute sorghum.

00:49:02.430 --> 00:49:05.680
For the white rice flour, tell
you just substitute millet

00:49:05.680 --> 00:49:06.180
flour.

00:49:06.180 --> 00:49:11.910
For the sweet rice flour, I tell
you to substitute potato flour.

00:49:11.910 --> 00:49:15.570
For the tapioca flour you
substitute potato starch,

00:49:15.570 --> 00:49:16.810
two different things.

00:49:16.810 --> 00:49:18.630
And then you use
the xanthan gum.

00:49:18.630 --> 00:49:21.369
So you're going to have
a different tasting mix,

00:49:21.369 --> 00:49:23.660
it's going to be a little
more flavorful because millet

00:49:23.660 --> 00:49:25.850
and sorghum taste has a taste.

00:49:25.850 --> 00:49:27.950
Also you may want to
grind the sorghum cause

00:49:27.950 --> 00:49:29.840
sorghum tends to
be kinda gritty.

00:49:29.840 --> 00:49:33.230
And the millet too,
kind of depends.

00:49:33.230 --> 00:49:37.720
Also be aware that the starch
is weirdly enough-- even

00:49:37.720 --> 00:49:41.540
tapioca starch will go bad-- way
quicker than you think they do.

00:49:41.540 --> 00:49:43.990
And I don't really
understand why.

00:49:43.990 --> 00:49:47.820
A lot of people tell me they
don't like tapioca starch.

00:49:47.820 --> 00:49:50.380
Now the weird thing, tapioca
starch and tapioca flour,

00:49:50.380 --> 00:49:51.680
same thing.

00:49:51.680 --> 00:49:54.460
Potato starch and potato
flour, not the same thing.

00:49:54.460 --> 00:49:55.980
So it's really complicated.

00:49:55.980 --> 00:49:57.940
But what I found
is starches tend

00:49:57.940 --> 00:50:00.420
to go very rancid very quickly.

00:50:00.420 --> 00:50:03.190
And people would tell me they
don't like tapioca flour often

00:50:03.190 --> 00:50:05.620
its they don't like
